  "slug": "french-toast-casserole",
  "title": "French Toast Casserole",
  "subtitle": null,
  "excerpt": "French Toast Casserole. A home-cook's recipe from Rebecca's collection, kept in the family rotation.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "From Rebecca's personal cookbook, a recipe she's made many times in her own kitchen.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "French toast casserole is a baked version of French toast: bread cubes soaked overnight in an egg, milk, and cinnamon custard, then baked in the oven until golden and just set. It serves a crowd from one dish and does almost all its work the night before.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Use bread that is a few days old, or dry it out in the oven first. Soft fresh bread turns to mush in the custard overnight. The bake time varies: start checking at 35 minutes. The casserole is done when the top is golden and the custard in the centre is set, not wobbly.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
